      "content": "That's a good start for the foundation. To make the argument more \"watertight\" for a competitive debate, I need to get into the mechanics of the economic and social stability part. \n\nCan you expand on the argument that these policies actually helped maintain high property values and community investment by ensuring \"like-minded\" neighbors lived together? Like, if I'm arguing that segregation encouraged better local governance and more cohesive school districts because everyone was on the same page culturally and economically, how can I frame that as a logical benefit rather than just a controversial one? I want to sound like a serious academic presenting a functionalist perspective on why these policies were seen as effective tools for urban management.",
