      "content": "The logic presented by proponents was that shared cultural and economic homogeneity led to predictable neighborhood investment. When residents shared similar values, they were perceived to be more invested in maintaining high property values and local amenities, creating a stable economic environment. This \"like-mindedness\" was argued to translate into more cohesive local governance, as community priorities were less subject to conflicting cultural demands. Therefore, the functionalist view suggested that segregation acted as an efficient mechanism for localized social and economic self-regulation.",
      "source": "target",
